The foods you eat are the first and most important thing you can change if you’re trying to improve your metabolic health.

This is because they directly impact your blood sugar levels, and keeping these levels balanced has powerful implications for your short- and long-term health — including preventing or reversing insulin resistance, increasing energy, improving mood, balancing hormones, weight loss, and more.

If you’re eating with the aim to improve your blood sugar, a general rule of thumb is to add lots of colorful vegetables to your plate, make sure you’re getting enough fiber, and eat 30+ grams of protein protein and healthy fats with most of your meals.

Berries — especially raspberries, blackberries, elderberries, and blueberries — are one of the richest sources of anthocyanins, a kind of antioxidant that fights free radicals (which play a major role in aging, inflammation, and chronic disease).

Scientists have found that berries may even help reverse insulin resistance.

One study that focused on anthocyanin consumption found that 67% of diabetic subjects experienced improved insulin sensitivity after drinking a smoothie with 22.5 grams of blueberry powder twice a day for 6 weeks.

Berries are also one of the best fruits to eat because they’re loaded with soluble fiber and lower on the glycemic index, meaning they won’t cause big blood sugar spikes.

Just one cup of raspberries, for instance, has around 8 grams of fiber (the recommended daily intake is between 25 and 35 grams).

The low-fat craze has largely been busted, and science has made it clear that eating a diet that contains healthy fats — especially unsaturated fats — is essential to metabolic health.

Avocados are one of my favorite blood sugar balancing foods!

Avocados are rich in monounsaturated fats, which have been shown to improve insulin sensitivity. This is a good thing! We WANT to be insulin sensitive, not insulin resistant!

Avocados are also high in fiber (a single avocado has around 10 grams — around 30% of your daily intake), which can help minimize post-meal glucose spikes.

What makes this such a star ingredient is its minimal flavor and endless versatility: add it to smoothies, desserts, dips, and dressing (to name several) for body and texture, or enjoy it as a side or topping to a ton of meals.

We’ve got 6 weeks of meal plans inside the Blood Sugar Fix that are packed full of blood sugar balancing ingredients, including avocados! 

There are so many delicious ways to use food to your advantage when it comes to metabolic health. It’s NOT about starvation or deprivation, but about pairing the right foods and utilizing a balance of nutrients.

Who you like avocado? What’s your favorite way to enjoy it?

By understanding where you are and what foods and habits are keeping your glucose levels stable, you can improve your metabolic health and, if it’s your goal, lose weight.

There is plenty of generic diet advice out there about things like wheat bread vs. sourdough, potatoes vs. pasta, but each of us has a unique response to food based on everything from genetics to microbiome. 

Experimenting to see which meals are actually driving the biggest glucose responses allows you to determine which foods to keep and which foods to kick.

You might be surprised by foods that you thought were good for you, or that were marketed as healthy, which are actually causing dramatic blood sugar spikes.

In addition to food, glucose monitors can be used to track how different habits like exercise, sleep, and meal timing, impact your blood sugar.

If you are trying to lose weight, it’s critical to keep your glucose levels within a healthy range and minimize drastic variations. This will decrease cravings, improve hormone balance, and increase insulin sensitivity — all of which are associated with weight loss.

Monitoring blood glucose gives a picture of where you currently are and lets you track changes over time, allowing you to understand what habits will improve your metabolic health, balance your hormones, and make weight loss possible.

Every year, the Environmental Working Group (EWG) analyzes the most recent USDA data to compile its infamous Clean 15 and Dirty Dozen lists.

These list the types of fruits and vegetables that tend to be grown with the most and least pesticides, based on the latest available numbers.

PSA: Don't take this as a sign that you should be avoiding any fruits or vegetables altogether—even the ones considered "dirty."

You can think of these lists more as resources to help guide your produce purchasing habits. If you only have a certain amount of money to spend at the grocery store, the Dirty Dozen and Clean 15 can steer you toward the produce you should prioritize buying organic from a health perspective.

It's important to point out that eating a non-organic strawberry is still by and large a healthier choice than eating, say, a strawberry-flavored gummy bear. Filling your plate with a variety of fresh fruits and veggies will always be a cornerstone of good nutrition.

To come up with this year's list, the EWG parsed through USDA data on 46,569 samples of 46 of the most popular fruits and veggies. The USDA washed and peeled them as one would do at home before testing them for pesticides.

After washing, nearly 75% of non-organic fresh produce sold in the U.S. contained residues of pesticides, the report found.

To rank each type of produce from "clean" to "dirty," the EWG assigns it a score based on the percent of samples tested with detectable pesticides; percent of samples with two or more detectable pesticides; average number of pesticides found on a single sample; average amount of pesticides found; maximum number of pesticides found on a single sample; and total number of pesticides found on the crop.

Here is the most recent list:

🌶️ Bell & Hot Peppers

I hope this helps you as you’re shopping and deciding what to prioritize buying organic! I highly recommend buying these 👆🏻 fruits & veggies organic when you can. ♥️

Eating for energy? Curious why animal protein is more nutrient efficient? Listen in for my take!

Guess what ALL of these foods have in common?

They can lead to insulin resistance!

Dried fruit, fruit juice, bread and cereal all break down quickly into glucose and cause a high demand for insulin.

Insulin is a STORAGE hormone!

Giving up refined sugar is a great idea if you’re looking to lose weight or offset insulin resistance, but substituting “sugar-free” and artificially sweetened versions of your favorite sodas and teas may affect your glucose tolerance and insulin sensitivity via other pathways in the body. 

Sucralose (Splenda) and saccharin (Sweet ‘N Low) have been shown to change the composition of bacteria in the gut and even impair glycemic response in healthy adults, and some artificial sweeteners trigger an outsized insulin response — i.e., even though they aren’t raising your glucose levels, your body still overproduces insulin, which can promote fat storage.

We need more research to make definitive claims, but the bottom line is that switching from refined sugar to artificial sweeteners doesn’t address the bottom lie: sugar cravings and sensitivity to sweetness.

1️⃣ More Muscle = More Calorie Expenditure

Maybe this is a mom in her late 30’s speaking, but I notice a lot of my peers sidelines by aches and pains. Let’s keep those joints mobile and strong!

When contrasted head-to-head against cardiovascular exercise, resistance training comes out on top in the battle to burn calories.

Strength training greatly improves sleep quality, aiding in your ability to fall asleep faster, sleep deeper, and wake less often during the night.

Rather than reaching for that early afternoon cup of coffee, grab a barbell. Exercise increases your energy in the moment and throughout the remainder of the day.

6️⃣ Protects Bone Health
Resistance training is an excellent way to combat loss of bone mass, and it decreases the risk of osteoporosis.

7️⃣ Decreases Anxiety & Lifts Mood
A meta-analysis of 33 clinical trials published in the peer-reviewed journal JAMA Psychiatry in 2018 found that participants who performed resistance training showed a significant reduction in symptoms of depression.

8️⃣ Stress Relief
Researchers have consistently found that those who regularly strength train tend to manage stress better and experience fewer adverse reactions to stressful situations as those who do not exercise.

Combining compound movements with little rest in between will get your heart rate going. You can reap all the aerobic benefits of cardio without conventional methods like running!

Stress is a normal physiological process, but how does it impact our metabolic health?

Whether physical or emotional, your bodily response is similar. However, two types of stress that have very different effects on health are acute and chronic stress.

🚨 Acute stress is an immediate, “fight-or-flight” response to any real or perceived threat.

Your brain sets alarm bells off to the central nervous system, which then increases your heart rate, blood pressure, and blood glucose levels, giving you the energy to run from or fight off an attack from a larger predator.

😩 Chronic stress is repeated exposure to physically or emotionally stressful situations that, over time, can lead to metabolic dysfunction. Chronic stress causes your body to remain in that high-alert state for longer than it was meant to, which eventually causes your insulin and glucose responses to break down, putting you at a higher risk of fatigue, poor food choices, weight gain, insulin resistance, and cardiovascular disease.

Getting rid of stress in your life can be a challenge, especially since it’s not always easy to opt out of stressful situations.
 
But knowing how to manage your response in the face of stress can make all the difference — and prevent the onset of chronic stress.

Here are my 5 Favorite Stress-Relieving Activities:

🧘🏼‍♀️ Breathwork: Breathwork will will help slow your breathing, slow your heart rate, and calm your nervous system, which studies have shown can help lower cortisol levels and reduce blood glucose.

🏋🏼‍♀️ Exercise: Just 10 minutes of low-intensity exercise can improve your mood, and upwards of 10 minutes of walking can help reduce blood pressure and cortisol levels, which in turn can help reduce blood glucose.

🌲 Being in Nature: Studies show that getting out of the house and into some green space can help you reduce cortisol levels, increase feelings of calmness, and kick that acute stress.

We all know exercise is good for us, but as a busy mom it can be hard to carve out time every day for a workout. You want to make sure that when you do exercise you’re getting the most bang for your buck and engaging in the types of workouts that are not only beneficial for all areas of health, but specifically preventing insulin resistance and improving metabolic health.

This is why you should prioritize resistance training and work on big muscle groups.

Research shows that full-body strength training that engages multiple muscle groups and challenges flexibility and endurance - think squats, pushups, planks - improves metabolic health markers like glucose regulation.

It’s so cool to see this reflected in your own CGM data and watch your glucose levels lower with exercise overtime.

Exercise has short- and long-term effects on blood glucose.

In the short term, exercise will increase the uptake of glucose by the muscles both during and after a workout. As a result, glucose will leave the bloodstream faster — lowering your blood glucose levels. Your muscles will use this glucose for immediate energy and store the rest for later.

Want more energy, less belly fat, stronger muscles, and to just feel great?
 
It's actually easier than you might think…
 
Just eat a protein-rich breakfast.

Here are FOUR reasons to start your day with at least 30 grams of protein in your first meal:

1️⃣ Research shows that eating a high-protein breakfast helps stabilize blood sugar for all-day energy, and can promote weight loss.
 
2️⃣ High protein breakfasts reduce ghrelin (the “hunger hormone” that tells your body to eat) and can even lessen cravings for unhealthy foods later in the day.
 
3️⃣ Muscles require leucine to be stimulated. Leucine is one of the essential amino acids; we must get it from our diet. We need 30 grams of protein to trigger this stimulus. You must reach that amino acid threshold in the blood to trigger this response.

4️⃣ Eating protein gives your body the building blocks for repairing the muscle tears that happen during a workout or just day-to-day life so you can recover and get stronger. We also need protein for hormones and neurotransmitters.

This caught my eye when I was whipping up a frozen treat for lunch the other day:

An entire CUP of cottage cheese has the same amount of calories as two TABLESPOONS of nut butter. 😱

Have you ever measured out nut butter on a food scale? This is something I encourage all my clients to do as nut butter is hard to eyeball and it’s easy to go overboard and wind up consuming 2-3x the serving you intended.

I love healthy fats and think you should incorporate them into every meal, but this was a great opportunity to highlight how food VOLUME contributes to satiety.

We have satiety hormones that are released when our stomach lining is physically stretched. Eating food that has bulk to it helps us feel full and satisfied from our meals.

Fat contributed to satiety in its own way too!

Fat contains 9 calories per gram.
Carbs and protein contain 4 calories per gram.

Fat is DOUBLE the calories, so it packs a greater caloric punch for a smaller volume of food.  This makes it easier to over eat.

In this example, a cup of cottage cheese is going to feel more filling and take longer to eat. Two tablespoons of nut butter is easy to lick off the spoon before it even makes it to your sandwich!

So yes, I’m adding the nut butter to my meal, but I’m also having foods with more “bulk” that will help me feel full: cottage cheese and blueberries.

Non-exercise activity thermogenesis, or NEAT, refers to calories burned during everyday activities rather than formal exercise.

For example, the energy you expend during a walk to work, cleaning the house or even fidgeting while you sit down all fall under the NEAT umbrella.

NEAT is just as important as exercise (maybe more so).

Most of the time when we think about pursuing health goals we place greater emphasis on our workouts in the gym, undervaluing the contribution of NEAT.

NEAT is often responsible for burning more calories than formal exercise and is an essential tool for those working towards body recomposition goals, such as weight loss.

Another thing I love about NEAT is that it’s an effective way to increase energy expenditure without increasing appetite.

I’ve worked with many clients who double their workout time in the gym in an effort to lose weight, only to find their appetite skyrocket. It’s easy to overeat the calories your burn during formal exercise!

Not only is NEAT a great way to keep your weight in check, it increases energy, lowers blood sugar, boosts mood, and improves cardiovascular health.

Here are some ways I’ve increased my NEAT:

- Using a standing desk
- Having a daily step goal
- Household chores
- Yardwork
- Cooking
- Playing w/ my kids
- Taking the stairs
- Stretching while I read
- Parking far away from store entrances
- Walking when I’m on the phone
- Taking walks with my husband to talk about our days instead of sitting on the couch

From your mental health to your weight, your sex life to your sleep — there’s a link to blood glucose, which is why stabilizing your levels is such a powerful tool.

Here’s what you can expect from managing blood sugar levels:

1️⃣ Stable Energy & Increased Focus

Elevated blood sugar can lead to feeling sluggish, fatigued, or give you brain fog. When your blood glucose is well managed and insulin sensitivity increases, you reap the benefits of sustained energy and kick the afternoon slump. 

2️⃣ Improved Moods

Research has linked high glycemic variability, specifically instances of glucose spikes and crashes, with feelings of irritability, anxiousness, and stress. Keeping glucose in range and avoiding extreme fluctuations can help manage mood swings and keep you more alert and upbeat rather than fighting negative feelings and crankiness. 

3️⃣ Fewer Cravings

When you eat foods high in refined carbohydrates, your blood glucose surges, which leads to the overproduction of insulin to keep up with the spike. Once the insulin overproduction catches up, your glucose crashes, leading you to crave something sweet to bring your glucose up to normal levels, and the cycle continues. By getting your blood glucose in check, you can get off the glucose rollercoaster and bust the cravings.

4️⃣ Better Skin

A spike in blood glucose causes a rise in insulin levels, which can increase the production of sex hormones called androgens, which are tied to skin health. When insulin levels are high, androgens lead to increased production of sebum and keratinocytes, which can leave skin feeling thick and oily and lead to unwanted breakouts. Studies have shown that having a low glycemic diet can lead to a reduction in acne problems.

Confused about how much protein you should be eating each day? I’m going to make this real simple for you.

If you have a goal to lose or gain weight you are going to make this calculation based off your goal weight, or what a healthy weight for you would be.

If you are looking to maintain, choose your current weight.

Take that number and multiply it by .8 and by 1. Those two numbers are your daily range of protein in grams.

Goal weight is 150 lbs? Your range is between 120-150 grams of protein.

If you workout, I recommend going on the higher end of that range.

If you’re more sedentary, you’re probably fine on the lower end.

We want protein intake to be somewhat consistent through the day. It doesn’t have to be exact, but you don’t want to go below 30 grams in a meal.

If your goal is 120 grams per day you could aim for 40 grams per meal.

Or, you could go heavier protein at breakfast and a little lower with dinner (B = 50 grams, L = 40, D = 30).

Maybe you aim for three meals with 30 grams each and then 30 with a post workout protein shake.

Eat a snack between meals? Make sure it has at least 10 grams of protein.

There are three main reasons why 30 is the magic number.

It’s the minimum number of grams of protein I encourage my clients to eat in each meal.

1️⃣ Muscle Protein Synthesis
2️⃣ Blood Sugar Balance
3️⃣ Satiety

Muscle protein synthesis is the process of building muscle mass.

Your muscular system is the largest organ in your body, your metabolic currency, your reservoir for amino acids, and it plays a vital role in fighting inflammation. 

Muscle is the organ of longevity, and we build muscle more easily when we hit that threshold of 30 grams of protein per meal

Protein is the most influential macronutrient when it comes to blood sugar balance.

Protein takes longer than carbohydrates to digest, which slows down the absorption of glucose into the bloodstream. 

When it comes to satiety, protein strongly regulates the release hunger hormones that keep us feeling full and satisfied between meals. If you find you’re hungry 2-3 hours after a meal, chances are good you didn’t eat enough protein.

30 isn’t the maximum, it’s the minimum.

Most women need to be eating at least 100 grams of protein per day, so 30 grams in each meal + 10 grams in a snack will help you reach that goal.

Personally, I feel my best with 45 grams of protein in each meal and eating three meals a day. This helps me hit my goal of 135 grams of protein per day.

It seems simple but this one shift is a game changer!

Before kids I was 20 lbs heavier and spent TWO HOURS at the gym, six days a week. And no those 20 extra pounds were not muscle. 😆

I’d do at least 45 minutes of cardio and spend the rest of the time making my way through the strength training machines.

After Corbin was born there was no way I was going to spend two hours away from my baby every day just to work out. I knew exercise was important for my physical and mental health, but I had to figure out a way to work out smarter.

With each baby (now there are 3!) I got back into exercise quickly, but spent less and less time physically at the gym. Shockingly, I was able to lose fat and gain muscle after each pregnancy, and over time develop a physique that I liked better than when I was spending 12 hours a week at the gym.

Here is what I learned:

1️⃣ Sleep > Exercise

No seriously, you need to sleep in order to lose fat and gain muscle. Sacrificing sleep to workout was sabotaging my success.

2️⃣ NEAT is where it’s at.

Non-exercise activity thermogenesis; AKA walking. I started walking with my kids and intentionally being more active throughout the day. Surprisingly, that burned more calories than pedaling away on the elliptical for 45 minutes and was way more fun.

3️⃣ Strength Training is the 💣

I ditched traditional cardio all together to focus on strength, which increased my metabolism. When I did want to get my heart rate up I would do it with HIIT workouts or intervals to be more efficient with my time.

4️⃣ Weight loss and maintenance is 90% diet

This was when I dove head first into studying nutrition and realized that while there are hundreds of reasons why we should exercise, weight loss isn’t one of them. If I wanted to lose the baby weight and stay a certain size, I needed to focus on dialing in my nutrition.

I still LOVE exercise, but I’m much happier and healthier with my 30-45 minute workouts, 5x a week.

Is Thanksgiving going to be your undoing this year?

There’s this pattern I see with women year after year where once Thanksgiving hits it is all downhill until January 1st. It’s like the food and festivities sets something off that feels hard to bring back into control until the holidays are all over.

I know, I know… it’s all about “balance”… yada yada. What does that even mean?!

We don’t get to eat all the things, all the time, and not expect there to be consequences.

Here are a few checks and balances you can implement to avoid the feeling of being out of control. These actually WORK because they help balance your blood sugar, so you’re not fighting against your physiology.

So yes, eat the pumpkin pie, enjoy the Christmas cookies, drink the wine, but do these things too:

1️⃣ Eat 30 grams of protein with every meal. I promise if you make this a non-negotiable between now and the new year it will change your life.

2️⃣ Choose a “plus “one when it comes to food that are going to disrupt blood sugar.  Where we get into trouble is when we try to “plus 2” or “plus 3” at every meal. Some examples:

- Skip the bun on your burger so you can enjoy some fries.
- Pass on the bread basket so you can have a glass of wine.
- Choose dessert instead or an appetizer, not both.

3️⃣ Close the kitchen 3-4 hours before bed.

Often its those after-dinner food choices that get us into trouble. I mean, who is eating salmon and broccoli at 10pm?! Not me! If I’m eating something at that time of night its some kind of dessert I want to have in peace in front of the TV.

This leads to disrupted sleep which leads to less energy the next day and increased cravings. It’s a cycle we want to avoid! The easiest way to do that is to have your dessert right after dinner and then close the kitchen until the next morning.

🙏🏻 My hope for all of us is that we come out of the holidays having enjoyed the foods we love, feeling good in our bodies, and proud of the choices we made! Making progress on your goals is icing on the cake, or pie. 🥧

Did you know that digesting food takes an enormous amount of energy?

When we eat easy-to-digest foods (like blended soups and smoothies) it draws less energy from the body, allowing you to KEEP more of your own energy.

Eating protein and fat before carbs and sugar can help stabilize blood sugar levels for several reasons:

1️⃣ Slower Digestion: Protein and fat take longer to digest than carbohydrates. When you consume a meal that includes protein and fat, it slows down the digestion and absorption of carbohydrates. This gradual release of glucose into the bloodstream helps prevent rapid spikes in blood sugar levels.

2️⃣ Reduced Insulin Response: Consuming protein and fat alongside carbohydrates can reduce the overall glycemic response to a meal. This means that the increase in blood sugar levels is more gradual, leading to a more controlled release of insulin.

3️⃣ Increased Satiety: Including protein and fat in your meals can contribute to a feeling of fullness and satiety. This may lead to slower eating and reduced overall food intake, which can further help in managing blood sugar levels.

From my experience, this is what I see produce the best results:

🐟 100 grams of protein per day, evenly spread across 3 meals.

🏃🏼‍♀️ Move every day! Whether that’s 10k steps, a dance workout, vigorously cleaning the bathrooms, or hitting the gym - keep moving.

💦 Drink half your bodyweight in ounces of water per day.

😴 Take sleep seriously! A minimum of 7 hours per night.

🥗 Eat 5 servings of fruits and veggies per day. Real food always wins!

☀️ Spend 30 minutes outside every day, no matter what the weather is like.

Do these things consistently for the next four weeks before you think about adding anything else in!

Seriously, you do not need to count your macros, take cold showers, or spend $100 on the latest superfood supplement until you have the basics dialed in.

Let the basics do the heavy lifting before you fine-tune.
